# Domain Zero Protocol - Code Ownership Rules
#
# This file defines ownership rules for protecting critical protocol files.
# See: https://docs.github.com/en/repositories/managing-your-repositorys-settings-and-features/customizing-your-repository/about-code-owners
#
# IMPORTANT: To enforce these rules, enable branch protection in your repository:
# 1. Go to Settings → Branches → Branch protection rules
# 2. Add rule for 'main' branch
# 3. Enable "Require pull request reviews before merging"
# 4. Enable "Require review from Code Owners"

# ============================================
# PROTOCOL FILES - RESTRICTED ACCESS
# ============================================
# These files define the core protocol and should only be modified
# by authorized administrators with explicit review process.

# Main protocol file - Most critical
protocol/CLAUDE.md @repo-admins

# Agent protocol files - Core system
protocol/YUUJI.md @repo-admins
protocol/MEGUMI.md @repo-admins
protocol/GOJO.md @repo-admins
protocol/NOBARA.md @repo-admins

# Protocol change log - Audit trail
protocol/GOJO-UPDATES-PATCH.md @repo-admins

# Tier system documentation
protocol/TIER-SELECTION-GUIDE.md @repo-admins
.protocol-state/tier-system-specification.md @repo-admins

# ============================================
# CONFIGURATION FILES - MODERATE ACCESS
# ============================================
# Configuration files that affect protocol behavior

.protocol-state/project-state.json @repo-admins
CODEOWNERS @repo-admins

# ============================================
# DOCUMENTATION - STANDARD REVIEW
# ============================================
# Documentation can be modified with standard review

README.md @repo-maintainers
LICENSE @repo-maintainers

# ============================================
# SETUP INSTRUCTIONS
# ============================================
#
# 1. Replace @repo-admins with your GitHub organization team or usernames:
#    Examples:
#    - @your-org/protocol-admins
#    - @username1 @username2
#
# 2. Replace @repo-maintainers with documentation maintainers:
#    Examples:
#    - @your-org/maintainers
#    - @username3 @username4
#
# 3. Enable branch protection in GitHub:
#    Settings → Branches → Add rule → main
#    ✓ Require pull request reviews
#    ✓ Require review from Code Owners
#    ✓ Require status checks to pass
#
# 4. For self-hosted Git (GitLab, Gitea, etc.):
#    - Configure protected branches
#    - Set up approval rules
#    - Add pre-receive hooks if needed
#
# ============================================
# ADDITIONAL PROTECTION (OPTIONAL)
# ============================================
#
# Git Hooks (local enforcement):
# Add to .git/hooks/pre-commit:
# ```bash
# #!/bin/bash
# if git diff --cached --name-only | grep -q "^protocol/CLAUDE.md"; then
#   echo "ERROR: Direct commits to protocol/CLAUDE.md are not allowed"
#   echo "Use: Read protocol/GOJO.md - Update CLAUDE.md [changes]"
#   exit 1
# fi
# ```
#
# Server-side enforcement (pre-receive hook):
# Contact your Git administrator to block direct pushes to protocol/*.md
